 vehicles with co-passengers. Chapters present a robust theory and methodology for studying communication in cars, how tasks are begun and ended, how people switch between tasks, how non-task talk appears, what ways and styles of communication drivers prefer, and how they expect the system voice to respond, among other things. Particular attention is given to cultural preferences as they are evident in this communication; these preferences are found to ground various trajectories in the use and meaning of in-car communication practices. The book explores these matters with a focus on the United States and Mainland China. Implications are drawn for the design and utilization of in-car communication systems.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aMobile communication systems. 0aMotor vehiclesxAutomatic control. 0aSpeech processing systems. 4aKraftfahrzeugelektrik. 4aMensch-Maschine-Kommunikation. 4aSignalverarbeitung. 7aCOMPUTERS / Database Management / Data Mining.2bisacsh1 aCarbaugh, Donal, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLie, Sunny, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMolina-Markham, Elizabeth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWinter, Ute, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCz978311065906108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE  DG 2019 Englishz978311061685908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of